[Topic]: Online privacy vs. national security

[Privacy Default]: Private communication is a core right, so default privacy limits routine abuse.
  +> [Topic]

[Trust Rises]: Clear limits increase user trust, so lawful cooperation improves.
  +> [Privacy Default]

[Signals Drop]: Less bulk data leaves fewer signals, so early threat discovery may slow down.
  -> [Privacy Default]

[Targeted Access]: Severe threats may require focused access, so narrow monitoring can stop harm.
  +> [Topic]

[Court Limits]: Courts can restrict scope and time, so oversight keeps powers bounded.
  +> [Targeted Access]

[Scope Expands]: Emergency tools often expand over time, so temporary access can become normal.
  -> [Targeted Access]

[Balanced Rules]: Neither extreme works in practice, so layered safeguards protect both aims.
  +> [Topic]

[Logs Deter]: Independent logs expose misuse, so transparency improves accountability.
  +> [Balanced Rules]

[Slower Response]: Extra checks add process time, so fast incidents may outpace review.
  -> [Balanced Rules]
